Good. That stomach drop is the lock clicking.

Here’s the answer: yes, lean into the “attention architecture” — but implement it in the dumbest, clearest possible way first. Metaphysical at the concept layer, brutally simple in code.

Don’t overthink. Decide this:

- Metaphor (locked in, no more debating):
  - Each URL = a building.
  - Domain = building style/type.
  - Time/visits = building height or width.
  - The street = your attention path; walking it = walking your mind.

Now: v0 implementation in the next 20–30 minutes.

Do this, in order:

1) Name it (30 seconds)
- Repo name: mirror-city-proto
- Description: “Walk your browser history as a street.”

Create it. No more blinking cursor.

2) Hardcode the mind palace (10–15 min)
- In the repo, make:
  - index.html
  - style.css
  - script.js (optional but helpful)

- For now: use a hardcoded array, no real history yet.

Example (paste this, then adjust, don’t start from zero):

In script.js:
const visits = [
  { url: "https://twitter.com", domain: "twitter.com", duration: 600 },
  { url: "https://github.com", domain: "github.com", duration: 1800 },
  { url: "https://notion.so", domain: "notion.so", duration: 900 },
  { url: "https://mirror.city/spec", domain: "mirror.city", duration: 300 },
  { url: "https://youtube.com", domain: "youtube.com", duration: 2400 },
];

const street = document.getElementById("street");

visits.forEach((v, i) => {
  const building = document.createElement("div");
  building.className = "building";

  const height = 50 + Math.min(v.duration / 10, 250); // duration → height
  building.style.height = `${height}px`;

  building.innerHTML = `
    <div class="label">
      <div class="domain">${v.domain}</div>
      <div class="url">${v.url}</div>
    </div>
  `;

  street.appendChild(building);
});

In index.html:
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
  <meta charset="UTF-8" />
  <title>Mirror City Proto</title>
  <link rel="stylesheet" href="style.css" />
</head>
<body>
  <div id="street-container">
    <div id="street"></div>
  </div>
  <script src="script.js"></script>
</body>
</html>

In style.css:
body {
  margin: 0;
  background: #050816;
  color: #f5f5f5;
  font-family: system-ui, sans-serif;
  overflow-x: hidden;
}

#street-container {
  white-space: nowrap;
  overflow-x: auto;
  overflow-y: hidden;
  height: 100vh;
  display: flex;
  align-items: flex-end;
  padding: 40px;
  box-sizing: border-box;
}

#street {
  display: inline-flex;
  gap: 16px;
}

.building {
  width: 80px;
  background: linear-gradient(to top, #38bdf8, #22c55e);
  border-radius: 6px 6px 2px 2px;
  position: relative;
  display: flex;
  align-items: flex-end;
  justify-content: center;
  cursor: pointer;
  transition: transform 0.15s ease, box-shadow 0.15s ease;
}

.building:hover {
  transform: translateY(-6px);
  box-shadow: 0 10px 24px rgba(0,0,0,0.4);
}

.label {
  font-size: 9px;
  padding: 4px;
  text-align: center;
  background: rgba(5,8,22,0.92);
  width: 100%;
  box-sizing: border-box;
  border-radius: 0 0 2px 2px;
}

.domain {
  font-weight: 600;
  color: #22c55e;
  overflow: hidden;
  text-overflow: ellipsis;
}

.url {
  opacity: 0.7;
  max-height: 22px;
  overflow: hidden;
}

This is your “mind palace, but dumb.” That’s perfect for v0.

3) Make it walkable (5 min)
- Let the street scroll horizontally. Already done via overflow-x.
- Optional tiny upgrade:
  - Add arrow-key navigation later. Not now. Shipping > polish.

4) Commit and push (3–5 min)
- git init
- git add .
- git commit -m "Mirror City proto v0: history as a street"
- Push to GitHub.
- Turn on GitHub Pages or deploy to Vercel/Netlify.
- Now you have a link. Even if it’s fake data, it’s a city. It counts.

5) Metaphysical stays, scope stays tight
- You ARE building it as attention architecture.
- But rules:
  - No new metaphors until you have:
    - A working street.
    - Real history wired in (next step, not now).
- The philosophy should be felt, not explained in a 2,000-word doc.
  - When people see it, they should go: “Oh. This is my brain as a street.”

Right now: implement that exact skeleton, push it, and tell me “link exists.” Then we lock the next move.
